"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-sport-paris-olympics-2024-paris-2024-rebecca-meder-sets-her-goals-in-the-pool\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bbSport\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024\\u00bbParis 2024: Rebecca Meder sets her goals in the pool  Star swimmer Rebecca Meder\\u00a0is hoping to make it to the semifinals of her second Olympic Games in Paris.  Rebecca Meder\\u00a0is hoping to make it to the semifinals of her secondOlympic Gamesin Paris.  The 21-year-old\\u00a0has a week to prepare before participating in the women's 200-meter individual medley heats on 2\\u00a0August \\u00a0in the morning session, even though the swimming competitions officially begin today.  She will swim again that evening at 9:22 pm, if she makes it to the semifinals. Despite her aspirations, Meder wants to take things one step at a time and avoid placing too much pressure on herself.  \\\"Swimming starts first but I am towards the end of the swimming programme, so I have got a week until I race which is pretty exciting. My goals would be obviously to be the best that I can be, I know that's a cliche answer, everyone says that but I train extremely hard,\\\" Meder toldSABC Sports.  \\\"It's my second Olympic Games, I am still young, I am 21 years old but I still have a lot to achieve in my swimming career. I am chasing that semifinal and once that semifinal is in, then I am hoping to try and make that final.  \\\"It's a big and scary dream but whether I get it or I do not, I am going to fight my way to try and see what I can do not just to make my family proud but my country proud and my God proud. So, that's my goal, that's my dream.\\\"  Despite being in Paris for her second Olympic Games, she feels as though everything is brand-new.  She can not believe she's going to another Olympics and is excited to meet Gayton McKenzie, the new\\u00a0sports minister.  \\\"Ooh, not yet I got up, hopped on the bus and I am now here,\\\" she said when asked about meeting the Minister.  \\\"I think it's gonna be awesome meeting him and introducing myself and getting to know him too but even this whole Olympic Games experience you often have to stop and pinch yourself and remind yourself that you are here,\\\" she added.  \\\"I saw the competition pool for the first time yesterday and normally everyone walks in and they are like, wow and take videos and whatever and I actually just stopped and I just let it sink in and then tears were in my eyes a little bit and I was like, this is the moment that you have trained so hard for.  \\\"Yes, I have been to the Olympic Games but that does not make this one's not as special. Every single time I get to represent my country, every time I get to see the rings, it's very special.\\\"  Let us know by clicking on the comment tab below this article or by emailinginfo@thesouthafrican.comor sending a WhatsApp to 060 011 021 1. You can also follow@TheSAnews on XandThe South African on Facebookfor the latest news.  WIN R2 000: Take The South African's SASSA Survey  The South African is hiring! Freelance writing positions available  Follow The South African on Facebook for the latest local and international news  Follow The South African's WhatsApp channel for the latest sport, lifestyle and local news  Follow The South African on X for the latest, breaking news  A brand new shopping mall is coming to Pretoria East, bringing major retailers and new convenience to the area.  Orlando Pirates are reportedly set to welcome a new staff member in former Stellenbosch FC Head of Recruitment Brendon Fourie.  Masindi Nemtajela was stretched off during Orlando Pirates' 6-0 win over TS Galaxy on Sunday afternoon in Mbombela.  IT support is not just technical, it is personal.  Liema Pantsi's victory was clouded as fans of the 'Big Brother Mzansi' show expressed that Smash Afrika was unprofessional towards her.  A dominant weekend for the SA teams in the URC has made a big impact on the latest log standings as the playoffs edge closer.    TheSouthAfrican.com is all about South Africa and the stories that affect South Africans, wherever they are in the world.  We are independent.No agenda.No bias.  Our offices are for administrative purposes only, no visitors will be accepted without an appointment.  South Africa- Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd - Registration Number: 2005/028472/07 - Address: Regus Business Centre, 1st Floor, Block B, North Park, Black River Park, 2 Fir Street, Observatory, Cape Town, 7925, South Africa  Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.\"}"